It is working as intended.  It renders the same value because you are rendering `{{selected}}` in every iteration of the template, and `selected` is set to whatever most recent value is emitted from `ChildComponent`.  What did you expect it to render?

As an aside, it is a poor pattern to use `@Input` to send data through multiple levels, from parent to child to grand-child.  This quickly becomes difficult to manage.  Even your very small code sample is already difficult to follow.

I suggest instead that you use a shared service, provided at the parent level

```
@Component({
  ...
  providers: [MyService]
})
export class ParentComponent {
  ...
}
```
You can then inject that service in parent and grand-child, and use the service to keep track of state.

There are several things off here. `componentWillReceiveProps` is considered unsafe and is [deprecated][1]. Try using `componentDidUpdate` [instead][2]. Also your class component needs a `constructor`. As it is now `state` is defined as a static variable.

